Here is a quick way to see each:

ⓐ  \(\sqrt[4]{u^{12}}\)  
Since \(u^{12}=(u^4)^3\),  
\[
\sqrt[4]{u^{12}}
=\sqrt[4]{(u^4)^3}
=(u^4)^{3/4}
=u^3.
\]  
(If you insist on the real‐principal 4th root and \(u\) might be negative, you’d write \(\bigl|u\bigr|^3\).)

ⓑ  \(\sqrt[3]{v^{15}}\)  
Because the cube‐root is an odd root, we simply divide the exponent by 3:  
\[
\sqrt[3]{v^{15}}
=(v^{15})^{1/3}
=v^{15/3}
=v^5.
\]

Here are the simplifications.  We use the fact that for an even‐indexed principal root you must take absolute‐value of what is left inside, but for an odd‐indexed root you do not.

a)  \sqrt[3]{27\,x^{27}}
   = \sqrt[3]{27}\;\sqrt[3]{x^{27}}
   = 3\;x^9.  
   (No absolute‐value is needed because it’s a cube‐root.)

b)  \sqrt[4]{81\,q^{28}}
   = \sqrt[4]{81}\;\sqrt[4]{q^{28}}
   = 3\;|q^7|
   = 3\,|q|^7.  

If you know in your context that q≥0, you can simply write 3 q^7.

